#Text=Conservatives win in a two-party parliament in Alberta , Canada
#Text=This is a prepared story , for when Jason Kenney receives approval for the pipe lines , or another important event occurs .
#Text=--
#Text=Gryllida
#Text=( talk ) 23:03 , 21 April 2019 ( UTC ) This article is a prepared story . It describes an event that is scheduled or expected but has not yet occurred .
#Text=If this article is ready to be developed , change the { { prepare } } tag to { { develop } }
#Text=Sunday , April 21 , 2019
#Text=On April 16 , 2019 , the United Conservative Party won 63 seats out of 87 in a provincial election of Alberta , Canada .
#Text=The party lead by Jason Kenney ended the New Democratic Party ' s single term in office , which saw Rachel Notley as premier .

#Text=Incidentally , this was the first time there had been a two-party government in the province since 1979 , with the Alberta Party and the Liberal Party having lost all their seats , as well as Freedom Conservative Party , Alberta Independence Party , Green and Independents .
#Text=Jason Kenney , the newly elected Premier of Alberta ( United Conservative Party ) .
#Text=Image : Andrew Scheer .
#Text=Rachel Notley , the previous Premier of Alberta ( New Democratic Party ) .
#Text=Image : Dave Cournoyer .
#Text=The election centred around the issue of the Trans-Mountain Pipeline , which the federal government tried to prevent the building of on the basis of environmental issues .
#Text=This project would involve restimulating the oil sands regions by building a pipeline into the neighbouring province of British Columbia , and would create more jobs .

#Text=This has resulted in more voters preferring to vote for the more conservative United Conservative Party , as its leader Jason Kenney said they would pressure the Prime Minister Justin Trudeau to approve this project .
#Text=An alternative of transporting oil by rail was available , according to the New Democratic Party .
#Text=In his pre-election campaign , Jason Kenney also said he would repeal the carbon tax in the province .
#Text=He said that it was introduced in exchange for approval of the Trans-Mountain Pipeline , but as the approval was unavailable , they would repeal the carbon tax .

#Text=Jason Kenney said , " We did n't see one single environmental group , provincial , municipal , government , First Nation , anybody move from ‘ no ’ to ’ yes ’ on pipelines as a result … all we got was stronger opposition to resource development and pipelines .
